        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1963-04-29T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1963-04-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="327"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d327">
                <head>327. Memorandum From President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2" type="from"
                        >Kennedy</persName> to Secretary of Defense <persName corresp="#p_MNRS1"
                        type="to">McNamara</persName>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d327fn0">Source: Washington National Records
                        Center, <gloss target="#t_OASD1">OASD</gloss> (C) A Files:<gloss
                            target="#t_FRC1">FRC</gloss> 71 A 2896, Cuba 381, Feb thru April 1963.
                        Secret; Eyes Only.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1963-04-29">April 29, 1963</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Are we keeping our Cuban contingency invasion plans up to date? I notice that
                    there have been a number of new judgments on the amount of equipment that the
                    Cubans have. I thought last October the number of troops we planned to have
                    available was rather limited and the success of the operation was dependent
                    upon, in large measure, our two airborne divisions getting in and controlling
                    the two airfields. It seems to me that we should strengthen our contingency
                    plans on this operation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">
                            <hi rend="strong">John Kennedy</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
